  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(-1\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\sin(1)\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(1\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>

<!-- Q4 -->
<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Sequences - Partial Sums of (-1)^n/n</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Let \(S_n = \displaystyle\sum_{k=1}^n \frac{(-1)^{k+1}}{k} = 1 - \frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{3}-\cdots\). Then \(\lim_{n\to\infty}S_n\) equals:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (A) \(\ln 2\)</strong></p><p>By the Alternating Series Test, this series converges. Its sum equals \(\ln 2\) — a classical result from Taylor series of \(\ln(1+x)\) at \(x=1\): \(\ln 2 = \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n}\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\ln 2\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(1\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[The series diverges]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>

<!-- Q5 -->
<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Sequences - limsup Inequality</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>For bounded sequences \(\{a_n\}\) and \(\{b_n\}\), which inequality always holds?</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) \(\limsup(a_n+b_n)\leq\limsup a_n+\limsup b_n\)</strong></p><p>This is a standard inequality: \(\limsup(a_n+b_n)\leq\limsup a_n+\limsup b_n\). Equality holds when one sequence converges. The reverse is false: take \(a_n=(-1)^n\), \(b_n=(-1)^{n+1}\), then \(a_n+b_n=0\) but \(\limsup a_n+\limsup b_n=2\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\limsup(a_n+b_n)\geq\limsup a_n+\limsup b_n\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\limsup(a_n+b_n)\leq\limsup a_n+\limsup b_n\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\limsup(a_n+b_n)=\limsup a_n+\limsup b_n\) always]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\liminf(a_n+b_n)\geq\limsup a_n+\liminf b_n\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>

<!-- Q6 -->
<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Sequences - Convergence via limsup = liminf</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>A bounded sequence \(\{a_n\}\) converges if and only if:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (C) \(\limsup a_n = \liminf a_n\)</strong></p><p>A bounded sequence converges iff all subsequential limits are equal, which is equivalent to \(\limsup=\liminf\). When this holds, the common value is the limit. This characterization is fundamental in real analysis.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\limsup a_n = 0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\liminf a_n > 0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\limsup a_n = \liminf a_n\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(|a_n| \leq 1\) for all \(n\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>

<!-- Q7 -->
<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Sequences - Ratio and Root Test Connection</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>If \(a_n > 0\) for all \(n\), then which relationship holds between \(\liminf\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n}\), \(\limsup(a_n)^{1/n}\), \(\liminf(a_n)^{1/n}\), and \(\limsup\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n}\)?</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (A) \(\liminf\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n}\leq\liminf a_n^{1/n}\leq\limsup a_n^{1/n}\leq\limsup\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n}\)</strong></p><p>This is a classical inequality: \(L_1\leq L_2\leq L_3\leq L_4\) where \(L_1=\liminf(a_{n+1}/a_n)\), \(L_2=\liminf a_n^{1/n}\), \(L_3=\limsup a_n^{1/n}\), \(L_4=\limsup(a_{n+1}/a_n)\). The ratio test is stronger than the root test in the sense that if the ratio test is inconclusive the root test may still be conclusive.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\liminf\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n}\leq\liminf a_n^{1/n}\leq\limsup a_n^{1/n}\leq\limsup\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\limsup a_n^{1/n}\leq\liminf\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\limsup\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n}=\limsup a_n^{1/n}\) always]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\liminf a_n^{1/n}\geq\limsup\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>

<!-- Q8 -->
<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Sequences - Cesaro Mean</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Let \(a_n = (-1)^n\). The Cesàro mean \(\sigma_n = \dfrac{1}{n}\displaystyle\sum_{k=1}^n a_k\) satisfies:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) \(\sigma_n\to 0\)</strong></p><p>For \(a_n=(-1)^n\): \(S_n=\sum_{k=1}^n(-1)^k = -1\) if \(n\) is odd, \(0\) if \(n\) is even. So \(\sigma_n=S_n/n\to0\). This shows the Cesàro mean can converge even when the original sequence diverges.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
