<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Sequences - Limit of Geometric Mean</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>If \(a_n\to L > 0\), then the geometric mean \(G_n = (a_1 a_2\cdots a_n)^{1/n}\) satisfies:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (C) \(G_n\to L\)</strong></p><p>Taking logs: \(\ln G_n = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{k=1}^n\ln a_k\). Since \(\ln a_n\to\ln L\), by the Cesàro mean theorem \(\frac{1}{n}\sum\ln a_k\to\ln L\). Hence \(G_n\to e^{\ln L}=L\). This shows that convergence is preserved under geometric means.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(G_n\to L^2\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(G_n\to 1\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(G_n\to L\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(G_n\to \sqrt{L}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>

<!-- Q18 -->
<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Sequences - Recursive: a_{n+1}=sqrt(6+a_n)</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Let \(a_1=1\) and \(a_{n+1}=\sqrt{6+a_n}\). Then \(\lim_{n\to\infty}a_n\) equals:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (D) \(3\)</strong></p><p>If the sequence converges to \(L\), then \(L=\sqrt{6+L}\), so \(L^2-L-6=0\), giving \((L-3)(L+2)=0\). Since \(a_n>0\) for all \(n\), \(L=3\). One can show by induction that \(a_n<3\) and \(a_n\) is increasing, so by MCT it converges to 3.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\sqrt{6}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(2\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\sqrt{7}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(3\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>

<!-- Q19 -->
<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Sequences - Convergence and Boundedness</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Which of the following is TRUE?</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) Every convergent sequence is bounded</strong></p><p>If \(a_n\to L\), take \(\epsilon=1\): for large \(n\), \(|a_n-L|<1\), so \(|a_n|<|L|+1\). Combined with the finite initial terms, the sequence is bounded. The converse is false (\((-1)^n\) is bounded but diverges).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Every bounded sequence converges]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Every convergent sequence is bounded]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Every monotone sequence converges]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Every Cauchy sequence in \(\mathbb{Q}\) converges in \(\mathbb{Q}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>

